The Lagos State government has started pulling down buildings adjoining the 21-storey structure, which collapsed on November 4, 2021 on Gerrard Road, Ikoyi. Forty-four persons were killed in the incident. The house was owned by the C.E.O. of Fourscore Heights Limited, Olufemi Osibona, who allegedly served as both contractor and developer. Osibona also died in the crash.   Hoodlums invade UNIOSUN hospital to retrieveâ€¦     Lagos inaugurates special anti-okada squad     Mama Boko Haram, two others jailed   A probe panel set up by the state government chaired a former Commissioner of Physical Planning & Urban Development, Mr Toyin Ayinde, has made various recommendations. The State Government has also directed the Office of the attorney-general and commissioner for justice to institute appropriate charges against the company that handled the construction of the collapsed building. The government equally said three edifices under construction at the site where the 21-storey building collapsed will be demolished. It said the exercise would start today, June 16, and be completed within three to six months. Commissioner for Special Duties and Inter-governmental Affairs, Tayo Bamgbose-Martins, who said this yesterday, added that the buildings would be demolished using non-explosives. He said the demolition of the structures would minimally impact the buildings and persons living close to the site.